Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics Package
- Added @vercel/analytics version ^1.6.1 to dependencies
- Used npm to install the package (project uses npm as package manager)
- Updated package.json and package-lock.json accordingly

### 2. Modified app/layout.tsx
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the closing `</AuthProvider>` tag
- Placement follows best practices for Next.js App Router architecture
- Component will track page views and web vitals automatically

## Files Modified

- **app/layout.tsx** - Root layout file, added Analytics import and component
- **package.json** - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- **package-lock.json** - Updated with new dependency tree

## Implementation Details

The implementation follows Vercel's official documentation for Next.js App Router projects:
- Analytics component is placed at the root layout level to track all pages
- Component is positioned inside the body tag but outside the main application providers
- This ensures analytics are captured for the entire application without interfering with existing functionality

## Notes

- The Analytics component will automatically track page views and Web Vitals
- No additional configuration is required for basic analytics
- Analytics data will be available in the Vercel dashboard once the app is deployed
- The implementation preserves all existing code structure and functionality
- The existing AuthProvider and ToastProvider components remain unchanged

## Testing

- Verified package installation completed successfully (@vercel/analytics v1.6.1)
- Confirmed TypeScript syntax is correct with proper import statements
- Verified component placement within the body tag structure
- All changes follow the project's existing code patterns and conventions

The build encountered an unrelated error regarding missing Supabase environment variables, which is a pre-existing issue not introduced by these changes.
